# Development Environment Rules: Using `uv`

This project standardizes on [uv](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv) for **environment management, dependency synchronization, and command execution**.  
You **must not manually activate Python virtual environments** (e.g., `source venv/bin/activate`).  
Instead, always use `uv run <command>` to ensure commands are executed inside the managed environment.

---

## 1. Environment Setup

### Install runtime dependencies only
```bash
uv sync
```

### Install with development dependencies
This installs tools such as **pytest**, **ruff**, **mypy**, and other dev tools:
```bash
uv sync --all-groups
```

> ⚠️ Always run `uv sync` (or `uv sync --all-groups`) after modifying `pyproject.toml` or dependency groups.

---

## 2. Running the CLI

The main command-line interface for this project is `indexed-cli`. Always run it with `uv run`.

### General help
```bash
uv run indexed-cli --help
```

### Create collections
```bash
uv run indexed-cli create jira -c my-issues -u https://company.atlassian.net --jql "project = PROJ"
uv run indexed-cli create confluence -c wiki -u https://company.atlassian.net --cql "space = DEV" --readOnlyFirstLevelComments
uv run indexed-cli create files -c docs --basePath ./documents --includePatterns ".*\.md$"
```

### Search collections
```bash
uv run indexed-cli search "auth methods" -c api-docs --json --maxNumberOfDocuments 5
```

### Update or delete
```bash
uv run indexed-cli update
uv run indexed-cli delete -c docs --yes
```

### Inspect and list
```bash
uv run indexed-cli inspect --json --include-index-size
uv run indexed-cli list
```

### Legacy commands
These are kept for backwards compatibility and should only be used when strictly necessary:
```bash
uv run indexed-cli legacy collection-search ...
uv run indexed-cli legacy collection-update ...
uv run indexed-cli legacy collection-mcp ...
```

### MCP Server
```bash
uv run indexed-mcp
```

---

## 3. Testing (pytest)

All tests are executed with `pytest` inside the uv-managed environment.

### Run full test suite with coverage
```bash
uv run pytest -q
```

### Run specific tests
```bash
uv run pytest tests/cli/test_app.py -q
uv run pytest tests/cli/test_app.py::test_create_jira_calls_service -q
uv run pytest -k "search and json" -q
```

### Disable coverage temporarily
```bash
uv run pytest -q -o addopts=
```

### Coverage report
After running tests with coverage enabled, open the HTML report:
```
htmlcov/index.html
```

---

## 4. Linting & Formatting (ruff)

We use [ruff](https://docs.astral.sh/ruff/) for linting and formatting.

### Run linter
```bash
uv run ruff check .
```

### Auto-fix linting issues
```bash
uv run ruff check . --fix
```

### Run formatter
```bash
uv run ruff format
```

---

## 5. Best Practices & Tips

- Always use `uv run <command>` for any tool (pytest, ruff, mypy, custom scripts, etc.).
- Keep environments in sync by re-running `uv sync` after dependency changes.
- Source code is installed from the `src/` directory using setuptools, which means imports like:
  ```python
  from cli.app import app
  ```
  will work correctly inside `uv run`.

---

✅ By following these rules, developers ensure that all environments remain reproducible and consistent, avoiding conflicts with system Python installations or unmanaged virtual environments.
